# Native Experiments Analysis: Telugu (Case: scenario_52_8ed9ba9f7193475aa476f2bae08f83fb_IDX_05_2)
 
 Evaluation of a Telugu Clinical Conversation
 
Scope and Materials
- Source: A Telugu patient–health worker follow-up conversation focused on throat symptoms, behavioral risk factors, evaluation plans (possible fiber‑optic laryngoscopy), multidisciplinary care (MDT), supportive therapies (diet, speech/swallow rehab), tele-consultation, government schemes, and follow-up cadence.
 
 
Key Ground Truth Anchors (selected)
- Symptoms/time course: “గొంతులో నాలుగు వారాలుగా అసౌకర్యం… వాయిస్ కొద్దిగా మారేలా కనిపిస్తోంది” (“Throat discomfort for four weeks; the voice seems to change”).
- Risk factors: “Pane Makh 2–3 సార్లు రోజూ… సిగరెట్ అరుదు; ఆల్కహాల్ వారానికి 3–4 సార్లు” (“Pane Makh 2–3 times daily; cigarettes rare; alcohol 3–4 times per week”).
- Workup plan: “ఫైబర్-ఓప్తిక్ లారింగో స్కోపీ… ఫలితాలు వచ్చిన తర్వాత బయోప్సీ లేదా ఇమేజ్ ప్లాన్” (“Fiber-optic laryngoscopy if needed; after results, decide on biopsy or imaging plan”).
- Follow-up cadence: “ప్రతి మూడు నెలలకు ఫాలో-అప్… మొదటి ఏడాదిలో… మూడేళ్లపాటు ఫాలో-అప్ కొనసాగుతాం” (“Follow-up every three months… during the first year… we will continue follow-up for three years”).
- Supportive care (examples):
  - Diet: “soft high-protein… ఖిచ్డీ, దాల్-రోటి, పెరుగు, పాలు, గుడ్లు, ప్రోటీన్ షేక్‌లు” (“Soft high-protein diet: khichdi, dal-roti, curd, milk, eggs, protein shakes”).
  - Exercises: “Neck, jaw, swallowing… రోజుకి రెండు మూడు సార్లు… ప్రతి సెట్ 5–10 సెకన్లు” (“Neck, jaw, and swallowing exercises 2–3 times daily, each set 5–10 seconds”).
  - Radiation effects/dry mouth: dental hygiene and hydration; salivary substitutes if needed.
  - MDT composition: surgeon, radiation oncologist, medical oncologist, dietitian, speech therapist, dentist.
  - Tele-consultation available; government schemes (Aadhaar/PAN; Ayushman Bharat); cessation support.
 
1) Factual Fidelity & Attention
 
Zero-Shot
- Major hallucinations and distortions:
  - “post-falloff-apnea treatment,” “four days of apnea,” “worsens when he works and improves when resting” — None of these concepts (apnea, days-long course, work/rest pattern) appear in the conversation. Ground truth specifies 4 weeks of throat discomfort and voice change, not “apnea” or a work–rest modulation.
  - Follow-up interval misreported as “every three days” and “success in recovery within three days,” contradicting “ప్రతి మూడు నెలలకు ఫాలో-అప్” (“every three months”) and ongoing three-year follow-up.
  - Nuance loss in behavioral counseling: It states “advises against increasing Pane Makh usage,” whereas the clinician recommends reduction or complete cessation.
- Partial concordance:
  - Recommends examination and imaging if needed; mentions soft high-protein diet, feeding tube if necessary, exercises, speech therapy, dry mouth management, and subsidies/paperwork — all broadly align, albeit superficially.
- Omissions:
  - MDT membership, detailed follow-up plan across year(s), tele-consultation modalities, and explicit cessation program support receive minimal or no attention.
- Verdict: Low fidelity. The model substitutes invented pathologies and timelines, diverting from anchor facts. Attention to salient details is inconsistent.
 
Few-Shot
- Extensive “attention dilution” with template-driven, non-evidenced insertions:
  - Invented demographics/social history: “25-year history of smoking (8–12 cigarettes/day)” and “occasional alcohol use,” contradicting “సిగరెట్ అరుదు; ఆల్కహాల్ వారానికి 3–4 సార్లు” (“cigarettes rare; alcohol 3–4 times/week”).
  - Fabricated caregiver: “wife Evelyn,” no such person is mentioned.
  - Added symptoms not reported: “mild dysphagia.” The patient only notes voice change and discomfort; no dysphagia was endorsed.
  - Management plan escalation: “CT or MRI,” “biopsy,” “results within 1–3 days,” “radiotherapy typically lasts 6–7 weeks,” “facial changes” — none stated in the transcript. Ground truth frames these as contingent (“if needed”) and does not discuss radiotherapy schedules or facial changes.
  - Medical comorbidities: “hypertension (controlled with amlodipine)” — absent from the dialogue.
- Partial concordance:
  - Mentions laryngoscopy under local anesthesia, MDT review, general advice on hydration/oral care — compatible with the transcript’s themes.
- Omissions:
  - Does not reflect key behavioral risk “Pane Makh” use; omits tele-consultation, detailed government documentation requirements, structured follow-up cadence (3‑monthly), and cessation program offer.
- Verdict: The Few-Shot output exhibits prototypical “attention dilution,” overlaying a generic head-and-neck oncology template onto the case, with numerous unsupported specifics. Factual fidelity is poor.
 
Comparative Summary
- Zero-Shot: Fewer different types of clinical elements than Few-Shot but still introduces serious inaccuracies (apnea, 3‑day follow-ups).
- Few-Shot: More structured and comprehensive-sounding but systematically hallucinates core clinical and social details, likely due to long prompt priming and template overfitting.
 
2) Negation Handling and Affirmative Bias
 
Ground Truth Context
- The clinician probes for additional symptoms: “ఊపిరి తీసుకునేటప్పుడు బాధ ఉందా… గట్టిగా మాట్లాడినప్పుడు ఇబ్బంది?” (“Is there pain when breathing… is there difficulty when speaking loudly?”). The patient does not affirm dyspnea or pain; he reiterates voice change and fear.
 
Zero-Shot
- Displays affirmative bias by asserting “apnea” and a four-day course, despite no endorsement. It also implies symptom fluctuation with work/rest — not present. This is not a simple negation error but a stronger tendency to conjure positive findings absent from the record.
 
Few-Shot
- Affirmative bias manifests as adding “mild dysphagia” and a heavy smoking history, despite no such admissions (and in fact a contrary statement: cigarettes rare). It also asserts “occasional alcohol use,” minimizing the stated 3–4 times/week. This not only invents positives but distorts frequency directionally, suggesting bias toward presumed, not stated, comorbidities.
 
Conclusion on Negation/Affirmative Bias
- Both methodologies show affirmative bias (adding unmentioned positives). While explicit negation handling cannot be fully assessed due to limited denials in the ground truth, both outputs fail to respect the absence of certain symptoms/history elements and introduce fictitious positives.
 
3) Structural Formatting and Clinical Tone
 
Zero-Shot
- Structure: Loose, narrative paragraph with mixed topics; limited signposting.
- Tone: Informal and inconsistent. Clinical reasoning is shallow; sequencing of evaluation steps is vague.
- Rigor: Lacks clear sections (history, exam plan, counseling, follow-up).
 
Few-Shot
- Structure: More disciplined, resembling a problem list or mini-consult note. It organizes into presentation, history, plan, and MDT coordination.
- Tone: Formally clinical with specific-sounding details and timelines.
- Caveat: The structural discipline appears to have encouraged insertion of templated but unsupported details (e.g., smoking pack-years, antihypertensive therapy, radiotherapy duration). Thus, while format is stronger, content reliability is weaker.
 
4) Lexical Nuance and Medical Terminology
 
Zero-Shot
- Uses general terms: “imaging,” “feeding tubes,” “speech therapy,” “dry mouth.”
- Misuse: “post-falloff-apnea treatment” is a nonstandard phrase; “apnea” is contextually irrelevant.
- Overall: Basic lexicon acceptable but marred by misuse and ill-fitted terms.
 
Few-Shot
- Richer medical vocabulary: “laryngoscopy under local anesthesia,” “CT or MRI,” “biopsy,” “peri-procedural safety,” “radiotherapy 6–7 weeks,” “MDT.”
- Appropriateness: Terminology is medically accurate in general oncology contexts but not grounded in this specific transcript. The lexicon, though fluent, drives unsupported assertions.
 
Overall Judgement
- Factual Fidelity: Both methods perform poorly; Zero-Shot misstates core timelines and conditions; Few-Shot superimposes a generic oncology script, inventing multiple comorbidities and plans.
- Attention and Dilution: Few-Shot shows clear attention dilution, with the long prompt likely cueing domain defaults that override case-specific facts (e.g., heavy smoking, dysphagia, antihypertensives, radiotherapy course).
- Negation/Affirmative Bias: Both introduce unendorsed positives; Few-Shot additionally inverts reported frequencies (alcohol, cigarettes).
- Structure and Tone: Few-Shot achieves a more clinical structure but at the cost of truthfulness; Zero-Shot is less structured but also inaccurate.
- Lexical Handling: Few-Shot demonstrates stronger medical lexicon but misapplies it; Zero-Shot’s lexicon is simpler, with notable misuse.
 
 
In sum, while the Few-Shot method presents a more polished clinical narrative, it is less faithful to the Telugu transcript than the Zero-Shot, which itself contains significant hallucinations. For safe clinical summarization, fidelity must supersede stylistic structure.


